[Sudh. keeps gigni with que e sor quae and a question aster mirum. Nothing born can stand against the etemal law of change, everything that springs from the womb of nature is seed laid for some future existence. But if Heraclitus was well known to represent fire as the element underlying all things, if Lucr. goes out of his way expressly to refute him (i. 635 sqq.) on tlzis very point, it seems incredible that our poet should introduce a reference to him, when he is arguing about fire, and yet never mention the word at all.]
